  "prompt": "College and NCAA Football: (NFL) In overtime, is the kicking team allowed to do an onside kick and if successful does the other team get the ball afterwards?",
  "response": "In both the NFL and NCAA (college) football, overtime rules differ significantly, especially regarding kicking plays like onside kicks. Here's a breakdown of how onside kicks are handled in overtime for each league:\n\n### **NFL Overtime Rules**\n\n1. **Possession Rules:**\n   - **Regular Season:** Overtime is a 10-minute period where both teams have the opportunity to possess the ball unless the first team with the ball scores a touchdown or a safety on its initial possession. If the first team scores a field goal, the other team gets a chance to possess the ball. If the game remains tied after both teams have had possession, it ends in a tie.\n   - **Postseason:** Overtime periods continue until a winner is determined, with similar possession rules as the regular season.\n\n2. **Onside Kicks in Overtime:**\n   - **Allowed:** Teams can attempt onside kicks during overtime just as they would during regular play.\n   - **Outcome if Successful:** If the kicking team successfully recovers the onside kick, they gain possession of the ball and can attempt to score again.\n   - **Outcome if Unsuccessful:** If the onside kick fails, the opposing team gains possession of the ball. There is no automatic allocation of the ball to the other team beyond the result of the onside kick attempt.\n\n### **NCAA (College) Football Overtime Rules**\n\n1. **Possession Format:**\n   - **Structured Alternation:** Each overtime period consists of each team getting one possession starting at the opponent's 25-yard line.\n   - **Determining the Winner:** After both teams have had their possession, if the game remains tied, additional overtime periods are played. Starting with the fifth overtime, teams must attempt a two-point conversion after scoring a touchdown.\n\n2. **Kicking Rules in Overtime:**\n   - **No Kickoffs:** Unlike the NFL, NCAA overtime does not involve kickoffs. Instead, each team starts its possession directly on offense at the 25-yard line.\n   - **Onside Kicks Not Applicable:** Because there are no kickoffs in overtime, the concept of an onside kick does not apply. Teams cannot attempt onside kicks during NCAA overtime periods.\n\n### **Summary**\n\n- **NFL:** Onside kicks are permitted during overtime. If the kicking team successfully recovers the onside kick, they retain possession and can continue their drive. The opposing team does not automatically receive the ball unless the onside kick fails.\n  \n- **NCAA (College):** Onside kicks are **not** part of the overtime protocol. Each team is given a possession from a set starting point (the 25-yard line), eliminating the need for special kicking plays like onside kicks during overtime.\n\nUnderstanding these differences is crucial for strategizing in overtime scenarios, whether coaching in the NFL or playing in college football.\n\n**References:**\n\n- [NFL Overtime Rules](https://operations.nfl.com/the-rules/nfl-overtime-rules/)\n- [NCAA Football Overtime Rules](https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-football-overtime-rules)\n\nYes in the NFL, a team can attempt an onside kick during overtime and, if they recover it, they retain possession without the other team automatically getting the ball. In NCAA (college) football overtime, onside kicks aren\u2019t part of the overtime format, so such kicks aren\u2019t used and the other team doesn\u2019t receive the ball afterward.",
